HEAD(1)                          User Commands                         HEAD(1)

NAME
       head - output the first part of files

SYNOPSIS
       head [OPTION]... [FILE]...

DESCRIPTION
       Print  the  first  10 lines of each FILE to standard output.  With
       more than one FILE, precede each with a header giving the file
       name.

       With no FILE, or when FILE is -, read standard input.

OPTIONS
       -c, --bytes=[-]NUM
              print  the  first  NUM bytes of each file; with the leading
              '-', print all but the last NUM bytes of each file

       -n, --lines=[-]NUM
              print the first NUM lines instead of the first 10; with
              the leading '-', print all but the last NUM lines

       -q, --quiet, --silent
              never print headers giving file names

       -v, --verbose
              always print headers giving file names

       -z, --zero-terminated
              line delimiter is NUL, not newline

       --help display this help and exit

       --version
              output version information and exit

   NUM may have a multiplier suffix:
       b 512, kB 1000, K 1024, MB 1000*1000, M 1024*1024, and so on
       for G, T, P, E.

NOTES
       Obsolete syntax -NUM (e.g., head -20) is also accepted.

EXIT STATUS
       0      if OK

       1      if errors occurred

AUTHORS
       LikeOS-64 project.

SEE ALSO
       tail(1), cat(1), less(1)

